Community Mentoring

Enrol A Child Now

Start Something.

Traditionally known as Big Brothers Big Sisters, our mentoring programs have grown in their diversity over the years. We’ll match your child with a Big Brother or Big Sister who will spend time with them out in the community. The focus is on positive role modelling.

Location: Edmonton, Strathcona County, Parkland County, Cold Lake, Lac La Biche, Morinville, Spruce Grove, Stony Plain & Vegreville
Kids Served: Kids between age 6 and 17.
Cost: FREE!
Enrollment Process:

  1. Application Form: Click here to submit your online application form. If you you’d prefer to submit a hard copy to our, you can download the application form by clicking here.
  2. In-Person Interview: We’ll contact you to set up an in-person interview where we’ll get to know the child so we can match them to the best volunteer. The interview typically takes 2 hours.
  3. In-Person Training: We’ll will contact you to set up in-person training for the child. We go over important concepts like boundaries and healthy relationships to make sure they’re starting their match off right.
  4. Matching: This is when we find your child a volunteer who is going to be a good fit. Please not that it can take up to two years for girls to be matched and up to four years for boys.

Inter­per­so­nal rela­ti­ons

Reco­gni­zing and opti­mi­zing our soci­al rela­ti­ons­hips

For sin­gles, part­ners, fami­ly mem­bers, col­leagues, rela­ti­ves, soul mates, etc. 


This NATHAL® semi­nar aims to detect and imme­dia­te­ly heal one’s own pat­terns of beha­viour and blo­cka­ges that make us expe­ri­ence inter­per­so­nal rela­ti­ons­hips as unsa­tis­fac­to­ry.

From a supe­ri­or, cos­mic-spi­ri­tu­al point of view, one learns to reco­gni­ze the effec­ts of one’s own beha­vi­or (and that of one’s partners/colleagues/friends etc. ) on our rela­ti­ons­hips.

The know­ledge gai­ned is not limi­ted to logi­cal-ratio­nal com­pre­hen­si­on. Rather, it is pos­si­ble for the par­ti­ci­pants to expe­ri­ence the under­ly­ing fee­lings, which makes a com­pre­hen­si­ve, holistic reco­gni­ti­on pos­si­ble. Healing takes place on the emo­tio­nal as well as on the ratio­nal level — one learns to per­cei­ve oneself and the partners/friend/colleagues in a holistic way, to see through con­flict situa­ti­ons and to avo­id them. The pre­re­qui­si­te for this is a gre­at emo­tio­nal and men­tal sta­bi­li­ty, which is per­man­ent­ly built up through the tuto­ri­als.

As a result, partnerships/relationships can chan­ge posi­tively. On the one hand, by reflec­ting a heigh­te­ned inner har­mo­ny in a bene­fi­ci­al way to the out­si­de through one’s own cha­ris­ma and to the insi­de in a genui­ne, intact part­nership. If it beco­mes clear in the semi­nar that a rela­ti­ons­hip will be per­man­ent­ly unhap­py, such a cri­sis can be seen as an oppor­tu­ni­ty and a sepa­ra­ti­on can be coped with more easi­ly and effort­less­ly, sin­ce with the help of the Nat­hal® method all situa­ti­ons can be exami­ned in advan­ce and appro­pria­te infor­ma­ti­on can pave the way.

The tuto­ri­als deal with the fol­lo­wing ques­ti­ons, among others:

  • Which incli­na­ti­ons and beha­viours have I shown in part­nerships in the past?
  • How do my cur­rent part­ner or other rela­ti­ons­hip per­sons feel about me?
  • What wis­hes do I have in a part­nership, are they rea­listic?
  • What wis­hes don’t I live for? What does a hap­py life wit­hout part­nership look like, and is that desi­ra­ble for me?
  • Is the­re a soul mate for me, does it make sen­se to live tog­e­ther with him, am I rea­dy to get so deeply invol­ved with someo­ne?
  • Can I give enough, whe­re will I suc­ceed and whe­re won’t?
    What do I have to do to live an opti­mal part­nership and how do I feel in such a part­nership?

Semi­nar fee: EUR 1,380 (semi­nar dura­ti­on: 5 days)


Note: Par­ti­ci­pa­ti­on in an inten­si­ve cour­se is a pre­re­qui­si­te for atten­ding all advan­ced cour­ses and/or spe­cial semi­nars.

The Business of Influence:
Turning An Instagram Account Into A Career

Have you ever scrolled through Instagram and made a decision to purchase something based solely upon the recommendation of one of your favorite Instagrammers? Odds are, most of us who are active on social media have done just that. We call this being #influenced. Selling is an art that’s evolved throughout human history, and its latest, rapidly growing adaptation is social-media marketing.  Katy will touch upon how she got started as an Instagram influencer, the ways in which she set herself apart in a saturated space, and share her top tips for anyone looking to leverage his or her own influence into a profitable side-hustle. 

Katy is the founder of Savoring the Flavoring, a blog and Instagram account focused on nourishing foods your family will actually enjoy, through the lens of a no-holds-barred boymom-of-three. 

Katy lives in a small town just north of Atlanta, where she has created a work-from-home career partnering with brands such as Whole Foods, Thrive Market, Vital Farms, Kitchen Aid and many more.

So often, I've heard parents brush off their children's tantrums, backtalk, excessive worry, or power struggles along with THEIR OWN frustration, exhaustion, and resentment, thinking that things will magically get better in a few years. News alert: They don't; they usually get worse.

You never expected parenting to be a breeze, but you didn't expect to be knocked flat off your feet.

Many days emotions boil over; your senses are under full assault, and you've lost your space, your time. Your identity is as blurred as your sticky-fingered windows.

And when you've reached your last limit, you silently complain, rage, yell, or cry. Oh, how we cry.

Social media images are banging you over the head, showing us perfect got-it-together moms and their always adorable (and coordinated) kids, and this might negatively affect how you view your own family. You'd love to ask that mom how she handles a tantrum or backtalk, but that would mean admitting you aren't quite sure what to do. (Besides, do her kids even have tantrums?)

And many nights, you fall into bed exhausted, worried, and feeling guilty, wondering just how screwed up the kids will be.

But here's the thing:

It doesn't have to be this way.

To have a calm and happy future with your family, you have to make changes today.

So you might ask, "How on earth can I shape this tiny human into a healthy, well-adjusted adult?"

Well, friend, don't panic! Take a deep breath because this is where positive parenting comes in. Parenting is about more than just getting the kids to behave. It's about better family relationships, increased joy and connection, and raising resilient tiny humans.

The Positive Parenting handbook gives parents anywhere, on any budget, the power to transform their families TODAY. Real parents, real results!

For charts and cards I recommend printing on thick stock paper, so it's easier to hang, not as flimsy, and can handle some wear ‘n’ tear.

For worksheets, activities and guides, I recommend printing and keeping securely in a three ring binder. Easy Peasy.

If you've purchased a handy chart or set of cards, this isn't necessary, but boy oh boy, it sure skyrockets things to the next level of fun. Do you have a laminator? (If you don't have one, I like this one). Laminate your resources (amazing). We all know kids are hard on things, so now you won't have to keep printing your chart and cards every time they get a little beat up.

Many of our charts also use Velcro stickers. And this is the icing on the cake. Attach one side of the Velcro sticker to the task card, and one side to the chart. Ensure that you don't mix up the sides. (i.e., the "hook" side should be on the chart, and the "furry" side on the cards.) Now you can move the cards around at your leisure. (Plus it's SUPER fun for kids).
